A bone house also fascinates after 100 years. Check out the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are up-to-date fish mills.
This is the Casa Batlló of Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
The house with its organic forms was named "Knochenhaus" by the local inhabitants.
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tiles and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of sheds and omnipresent soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau of Antonio Gaudi.
The facade of the house plays with dreamy lines, tender colors and textures that remind of nature and living beings.
It is only in a closer look that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
During the night, the whole facade appears even more plastic, dramatic and the special illumination enhances the shine of the colors.
The same winding lines and devoured shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, rails, decorative elements of doors, even beech holes and bars.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the lively Passeig de Grácia No. 43 shopping street was built by the reconstruction of a house from 1877, which architect Emilio Sala Cortese carried out.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old building and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed to the idea of Gaudí for an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
However, the house Casa Batlló did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
The decorations for the representative home of the real-life owner and also the use of mosaics on the facade were created on its drawing board.
However, numerous other artists and artists also cooperated in the design of the facade.
The joint work on the drafts for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá in the Güell Park, where there are other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was given by the local inhabitants of its organic forms because of the nicknames "Knochenhaus".
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "fine house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George the Patron of Catalonia.
But other sculptoric elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed for the house a central heating system that was unique for the time being with ventilation channels and typical fireplaces.
Something bizarre already seems to be her 45 degree inclination.
In his work Gaudí consistently ignored all the construction regulations at the time and was by no means allowed by them.
Before the construction began, however, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he had provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city fathers were so horrified at the completion two years later by the result that they demanded relief.
Among other things, the councillors also found that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
On the contrary, only fifteen days after the city district's call for changes, Josep Batlló made a request to approve the renting of the two highest floors of the house - and it was given to him without delay.
The houseowner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the second floor gallery there was a social salon, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were removed by the basic elements of the conversion and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of rooms.
The social part can be completely combined by opening the salon doors and thus a larger society could easily chat without having to give up a certain intimacy in more confidential discussions.
The house received a rather unusual roof and two more floors by Gaudí's conversion in addition to a new facade.
Gaudí's play is also impressive with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is disguised and the light courts.
The play of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum amount of light.
He simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors that absorb sunlight on the contrary.
The house Casa Batlló, which was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can visit anyone today.
On the first floor is the most spacious and magnificent apartment made available to the public.
The homeowners decided only in the year on this step and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous Creator.
When it was found that this was a rather eligible business, the visits were maintained, even they were extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
The price to visit the building monument, however, is not a cardboard stalk, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the admission prices to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the householders and visit him at home.
