A longer index finger than ring finger means a lower risk of developing cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously exposed to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is supposed to be related to the mirror of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixty," said the co-author of the study, Ros Eeles, professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health stress, added Mrs Eeles.
In the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain persecuted more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3000 healthy men.
With more than half of the participants in the study, the pointing finger was shorter than the ring finger on the right hand.
For these men, prostate cancer was the same as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were equal in length.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, in men up to 60, even by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which form in the prenatal age, clearly reflects the different mirrors of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that the testosterone in particular accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, said ČTK that this study was known to him in a fleet, yet he did not consider the relationship between the finger length and the cancer risk to be "completely proven".
