Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novel because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures, one element can be replaced by another," Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon from the NASA Astrobiological Institute, which led the study, chose the Mono Lake due to its high arsenic content.
As arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, it assumed that microbes exposed to both might be able to replace one element with the other.
"The toxicity of arsenic is mainly due to the fact that it is chemically similar to phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another."
"But the difference is so great that arsenic works differently than phosphorus. It comes into our biochemical system where it almost lubricates everything," explains Anbar.
