Sports and regulatory environment
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show ingenuity, but not the will to avoid a penalty.
The exclusion of the game of 23 November against the Ajax in the Champions League (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) from the game led to a lot of ink being shed on whether it was an unsporting act or not and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is commonly known, the two players lost time a few minutes before playing (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and as the Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will fulfill the prescribed penalty at the next match against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game without any cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the coach of the club, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules that are followed in this sport.
Part of the debate on the case presented is that a team of the football club Real Madrid (who pretends to be nobleness and honor in his hymn and on other occasions punished his players for similar incidents) played the main role in this, and on the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate is about whether it does not expressly contradict the principles of sport prohibited by the statutes, i.e. whether these actions constitute a circumvention of rules. In fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of sports, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this matter, the damage caused to the sports spirit should be examined.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect which was not threatened by these actions, for it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid the unwarranted players taking an unjustified advantage of the counter-team.
The paradox of the action of the players of the Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally understand as a misplay or a circumvention, because the circumvention of the rule was not secretly executed to avoid a sanction, but it should be as striking as possible so that it is punished by the arbitrator.
The players waited and accepted the penalty joyfully.
Another question is what kind of advantage did the offenders draw from the intentional fouls.
It should be stressed here that the rival was not put in a more unfavorable position or gained advantages for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players then.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next game phase of the Champions League without any cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, up to a certain degree uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually leave. Furthermore, the players receive a penalty with this procedure and move into the second card cycle in which they leave for card accumulation with a card less than in the first cycle.
It is not so clear whether it is really an advantage.
In the end, such actions are not directed against the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions in order to benefit from the rules as much as possible.
In this case, the players did not want to avoid any penalty (that would actually be a clear case of regularity), they rather wanted to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding or fleeing a punishment.
Although the line between inventiveness and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of inventive step.
I have the impression that the polemics arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transfer.
The damage caused by these actions to the principles of sport is less ethical than rather aesthetic.
