Worldwide Illumination Renewal Plan
Yesterday in Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries in order to achieve a reduction in greenhouse gas (FCC) which corresponds to almost one third of the additional reduction that needs to be achieved in order to stabilise the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments from the industrialized countries.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem would be avoided in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of the FCFCs delivered to the earth due to the lighting, if the white glowing pears, which still represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, would be replaced by fluorescent or better, by light diodes (LED).
The lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases of the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, the major emissions emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that should reduce global emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt should be deducted from this balance sheet in order to stabilise the increase in climate by 2 degrees Celsius from today to 2020 in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In the white glowing pears, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact light bulbs the energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED light bulbs this energy requirement is reduced by two times.
The compact light bulbs hold on average between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, such as those that the manufacturer Philips has launched this week - this company has participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white glowing pear, which gives an indication of the savings potential of the exchange plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that these completely new light bulbs provide very little heat, they can also work with a rule resistance.
And they contain no mercury.
Several specialists have pointed out that compact light bulbs have reserves, because they contain mercury and therefore have to be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in the developing countries, except for producers, provide an acceptance site.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact light bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants that emit much more mercury to produce the electricity wasted by the white-ambered pears.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would generate through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save a billion dollars annually in the purchase of electricity and eight million tonnes of CO2, which means an equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
