The apple imported from Brazil, which is intended as an interim meal for the study, shows traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide prohibited in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, including in lunch, where the study found traces of an insecticide which is strictly prohibited in the EU.
In addition, the hack steak, the tuna from the cans, even the baguette and the gum of pesticides and other chemical substances were sprinkled.
In the tap water, the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
During dinner, the salmon steak with 34 determined chemical residues was the "most rich", and even the plastic plate used to warm up the meal in the microwave was not unladen.
The final risk of this "pollutant cocktail" for the consumer "is probably undervalued", says the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV) has in turn proposed "in view of the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides in order to stop the "increasing civil disease".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) identified 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables, which are consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
